<section xml:id="section-activity-clo3">
  <title>Activity for CLO-3</title>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-clo3-review">
    <title>Conceptual Review</title>
    <p>
      You can test your learning from the video (and your own
      background knowledge) with the following review questions.
      Conceptual questions on quizes may be taken from these review
      questions. 
    </p>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Why is intersection an important conceptual connection
          between algebra and geometry?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Intersection is the geometric equivalent of solving
          equations. If I have two equations in two variables, their
          common solution is the set of variable values that satisfy
          both equation. But equations in two variables are loci in
          <m>\RR^2</m> when interpreted geometrically. The values of
          the variables that solve both equations are precisely the
          coordinates of the points which are on both loci. Therefore,
          intersection is just the geomtry version of solving a system
          of equations. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is the general algebraic method for solving
          intersections?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Solving intersection is the same as solving systems of
          equations. Solving system is best approached by isolating
          and replacing variables, to reduce a multi-variable equation
          into a single variable equation. Once you get to a single
          variable equation, hopefully that equation is solvable and
          the values of the single variable can be used to determine
          the other variables. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What complications can happen with intersection that involve
          conics? 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          For interesection of line, the isolate and replace can be
          done very algorithmically.  For conics, though, the choice
          of replacement variable can matter. Sometime, isolating and
          replace one variable leads to a much more difficult or
          complicated situation than using the other variable. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What does it mean to isolate and replace an expression?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Usually, solving system is taught with instruction to
          isolate and replace a variable. But is a variable only shows
          up as the same expression in both equations, then it is
          sufficient to isolate and replace that expression. If
          <m>x^2</m> is the only instance of <m>x</m> in both equation,
          then you can use one equation to solve for <m>x^2</m> and
          then replace <m>x^2</m> directly in the second equation,
          without ever having to use the square root to get to
          <m>x</m> itself. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-activity-intersections">
    <title>Calculation Questons: Intersection of Lines and Conics</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the intersection of the line <m>y = -2x -5</m> and the
          line <m>y = 9x+1</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Solving for intesection is algebraically the same as solving
          the system of two equations. In these two equations, the
          <m>y</m> terms are already isolated, so I can simply equate
          these two terms and solve for <m>x</m>. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
            -2x - 5 \amp = 9x + 1
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
            -2x - 9x \amp = 5 + 1
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
            -11x \amp = 6 \implies x = \frac{-6}{11}
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Then I can insert this <m>x</m> value into either equation
          to get the <m>y</m> value of the intersection point. (Either
          equation will give the same <m>y</m> value; if they don't,
          I've made an error somewhere). 
          <md>
            y = 9x + 1 = 9 \frac{-6}{11} + 1 = \frac{-54}{11} +
            \frac{11}{11} = \frac{-43}{11}
          </md>
          I conclude that the intersection point is <m> \left(
          \frac{-6}{11}, \frac{-43}{11} \right)</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the intersection of the line <m>3x-2y+4=0</m> and the
          line <m>y = 4</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Solving for intesection is algebraically the same as solving
          the system of two equations. In the second equation,
          <m>y</m> is already isolated, so I can replace <m>y</m> in
          the first equation. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
            3x - 2y + 4 \amp = 0 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
            3x - 2(4) + 4 \amp = 0
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
            3x - 4 \amp = 0 \implies x = \frac{4}{3}
            </mrow>
          </md>
          I already know that <m>y</m> value must be 4, so this gives
          me the intersection point: <m>\left( \frac{4}{3}, 4
          \right)</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the intersection of the line <m>3y - x - 5 = 0</m> and
          the circle <m>x^2 + y^2 = 25</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Solving for intesection is algebraically the same as solving
          the system of two equations. If I isolate <m>x</m> in the
          first equation, I get <m>x = 3y - 5</m>. I can use this to
          replace <m>x</m> in the second equation and expand to get a
          quadratic equation.
          <md>
            <mrow>
            \left( 3y - 5 \right)^2 + y^2 \amp = 25
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
            9y^2 - 30y + 25 + y^2 \amp = 25
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
            10y^2 - 30 y \amp = 0 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
            10y(y - 3) \amp = 0 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          The roots of the quadratic are 0 and 3, so those are the
          <m>y</m> values of the intersection points. I can use
          either equation to calculate the matching <m>x</m> values;
          I choose to use the isolated version of the first equation,
          since it is the most efficient.
          <md>
            <mrow>
            y \amp = 0 \implies x = 3y - 5 = 3(0) - 5 = -5 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
            y \amp = 3 \implies x = 3y - 5 = 3(3) - 5 = 4
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Therefore, the two intersection points are <m>(-5, 0)</m> and
          <m>(4,3)</m>. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the intersection of the line <m>x - y + 4 = 0</m> and the
          hyperbola <m>\frac{x^2}{1} - \frac{y^2}{4} = 1</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Solving for intesection is algebraically the same as solving
          the system of two equations. In the first equation,
          I can isolate <m>y</m> to get <m>y = x+4</m>. I can
          use this to replace <m>y</m> in the equation of the
          hyperbola.
          <md>
            <mrow>
            x^2 - \frac{1}{4} (x+4)^2 \amp = 1 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
            4x^2 - (x+4)^2 \amp = 4 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
            4x^2 - x^2 - 8x - 16 \amp = 4 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
            3x^2  - 8x - 20 \amp = 0 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          This is a quadratic; the quadratic equation tells me the
          roots.
          <md>
            x = \frac{8 \pm \sqrt{64 + 240}}{6} = \frac{8 \pm
            2\sqrt{76}}{6} = \frac{4 \pm \sqrt{76}}{3}
          </md>
          Then I can use the previous equation <m>y = x+4</m> to get the
          matching <m>y</m> coordinates. 
          <md>
            y = x + 4 = \frac{4 \pm \sqrt{76}}{3} + 4 = \frac{16 \pm
            \sqrt{76}}{3} 
          </md>
          All together, I have two intersection points. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
            \amp \left( \frac{4 + \sqrt{76}}{3}, \frac{16 + \sqrt{76}}{3}
            \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
            \amp \left( \frac{4 - \sqrt{76}}{3}, \frac{16 - \sqrt{76}}{3}
            \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          I could write the decimal approximates of these values.
          That might help me know where to draw them, but the above
          expressions are preferable as exact values.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the intersection of the circle <m>x^2 + y^2 = 16</m>
          and the ellipse <m>\frac{x^2}{16} + \frac{y^2}{4} = 1</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Unlike the previous activities, I know have two conics. In
          general, intersections of two conics can be quite difficult:
          four intersection points are possible, and sometimes the
          solution require dealing with a degree 4 polynomial. Where
          possible, I'll look for algebraic or geometric tricks to
          make the process easier.
        </p>
        <p>
          One important algebraic trick is substituting an expression,
          instead of just the variable. In the two equations for this
          activity, <m>x</m> shows up only as <m>x^2</m>, and likewise
          <m>y</m> shows up only as <m>y^2</m>. Therefore, I can
          isolate <m>x^2</m> (or, if I wanted, <m>y^2</m>) in one
          equation and substitute that in the other equation. I'll use
          the circle equation first.
          <md>
            x^2 + y^2 = 16 \implies x^2 = 16 - y^2
          </md>
          Then I can use this expression to replace the <m>x^2</m> in
          the equation of the ellipse. That will give a quadratic in
          <m>y</m>, which I can then solve. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \frac{(16-y^2)}{16} + \frac{y^2}{4} \amp = 1 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              1 - \frac{y^2}{16} + \frac{y^2}{4} \amp = 1
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \frac{3y^2}{16} = 0  \implies y = 0 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          With <m>y=0</m>, substituting this value for <m>y</m> in
          either equation will result in <m>x = \pm 4</m>. Therefore,
          there are two intersection points: <m>(4,0)</m> and
          <m>(-4,0)</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          There is an alternative approach here as well. It is often
          good to think about the geometry when solving intersection
          problems. In this problem, I have two conics centred at the
          origin. There is a circle with radius <m>4</m> and an
          ellipse with major axis of <m>4</m> in the <m>x</m>
          direction and minor axis of <m>2</m> in the <m>y</m>
          direction. Therefore, from the geometry alone, I can
          conclude that the ellipse sits inside the circle but that
          they both reach out to the points <m>(4,0)</m> and
          <m>(-4,0)</m> along the <m>x</m> axis. This gives me a
          geometric argument for the intersection points without any
          calculation at all. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the intersection of the ellipse <m>\frac{(x-4)^2}{25} +
          \frac{(y-3)^2}{9} = 1 </m> and the hyperbola
          <m>\frac{(x-4)^2}{25} - \frac{(y+2)^2}{16} = 1</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Here I have two conics again. However, the expression
          <m>\frac{(x-4)^2}{25}</m> shows up in both equations, and
          there are no other instances of the <m>x</m>. Therefore, I
          can solve for this expression in one equation and replace it
          in the other. Doing this is, by far, the most reasoanble
          approach. Solving for <m>x</m> or <m>y</m> and then
          substituting would be quite difficult, involving square
          roots. 
        </p>
        <p>
          I solve for the expression in the equation of the ellipse.
          <md>
            \frac{(x-4)^2}{25} = 1 - \frac{(y-3)^2}{9}
          </md>
          Then I replace the whole expression in the hyperbola. After
          that, I clear denominators, expand the binomials, and end up
          with a quadratic in <m>y</m> which I can solve. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              1 - \frac{(y-3)^2}{9} - \frac{(y+2)^2}{16} \amp = 1 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              -16(y-3)^2 - 9(y+2)^2 \amp = 0 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              -16(y^2 - 6y + 9)  - 9(y^2 + 4y + 4) \amp = 0 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              -16y^2 + 96y - 144  - 9y^2 -36y -36 \amp = 0 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              -25y^2 + 60y - 180 \amp = 0 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              y = \frac{-60 \pm \sqrt{3600 - 18000}}{-50} = \frac{-60 \pm
              \sqrt{-14400}}{-50} 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          There is a negative under the square root. Therefore, no
          <m>y</m> values are possible. I conclude that there are no
          intersection points. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
</section>
